title: Activation cross sections of deuteron-induced nuclear reactions on hafnium

x4freetext: Activation cross sections of deuteron-induced nuclear
reactions on hafnium

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.268, p.3443 (2010)

x4freetext: 21 MeV
High purity natural hafnium foils 10 micro-m from
Goodfellow.
Ti monitor foils (12 micro-m) and
Al (50 micro-m) energy degradation foils.
Deuteron beams of 21 MeV 80
nA beam intensities for 1 h was used. Targets were
irradiated in Faraday-cup type holder. Measurements
started from 90 min after EOB. The beam intensity
obtained via charge collection was corrected with the
data from the monitor reaction.
The energy degradation was initially determined by
calculation using the formulas and tables of Andersen
and Ziegler and corrected on the basis of the measured
monitor reaction excitation function. The nuclear data
were taken from the Lund database,
http://nucleardata.nuclear.lu.se.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.262, p.7 (2007)

x4freetext: Taking into account the cumulative effects of
possible incident energy variation and thickness of
the different targets, the uncertainty of the energy
of the front foil of a stack is around 0.3 MeV and
increases up to 1.0 MeV for the last foil of the
stack.
The estimated total uncertainty on the
cross-sections was about 8-13% by taking the square
root of the sum in quadrature of individual
contributions,  supposing equal sensitivities.
number of target nuclei (5%);
beam current (6%);
detector efficiency (5 -7%);
gamma-ray abundances (1-3%).
statistical error and peak area fit (1-8%)
Fitted excitation functions were used for
determination of integral physical yields.
